# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-law-review
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-law-review/agnes-flanagan-chapel] The chapel was built in a 16-side design with stained glass windows depicting stories from the Book of Genesis.
[src:animal-law-review/agnes-flanagan-chapel] Due to the chapel's 16 sides, it is home to a specially designed 1971 Casavant pipe organ which hangs from its ceiling.
[src:animal-law-review/agnes-flanagan-chapel] It is the world's only circular pipe organ, and was inaugurated by world-renowned organist Virgil Fox.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law-review] They can be admitted by virtue of their grades during their first year of law school.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law-review] They can also be admitted by participating in an anonymous writing competition held by all three law reviews at Lewis & Clark Law School during the summer months.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law-review] However, most members are admitted through a process in which students compete in a source-checking and editing competition at the end of their first semester of law school, then work as volunteer source checkers without academic credit during their second semester of law school.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law-review] The students who earn top scores in the source-checking and editing competition are invited to source check the following semester and the students who excel during that semester are invited to join the law review as full members in their second year.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Animal law permeates and affects most traditional areas of the law – including tort, contract, criminal and constitutional law.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] A growing number of state and local bar associations now have animal law committees.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The Animal Legal Defense Fund, founded in 1979, was the first organization dedicated to promoting the field of animal law and using the law to protect the lives and advance the interests of animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] In the Swiss canton of Zurich an animal lawyer, Antoine Goetschel, was employed by the canton government to represent the interests of animals in animal cruelty cases from 2007 through 2010, when the Zurich Animal Advocate position was abolished.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] In this capacity, Goetschel attempted to ensure that Swiss animal protection laws, which are among the strictest in the world, were correctly enforced.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The Animal Defenders Office is an Australian community legal centre focusing on animal law.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] In South Africa, Animal Law Reform South Africa is the first dedicated animal law organisation in the country working in the areas of 1.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] As of 2020, animal law is being taught in 167 law schools in the US and Canada, including Harvard, Stanford, UCLA, Northwestern, University of Michigan, Georgetown, Duke, and Lewis & Clark.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The comprehensive American animal law casebook is *Animal Law: Cases and Materials.* Because animal law is not a traditional legal field, most of the book's chapters are framed in terms of familiar subsets of law such as tort, contract, criminal and constitutional law.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Each chapter sets out cases and commentary where animal law affects those broader areas.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The *Animal Protection Laws of the United States of America & Canada* compendium, by Stephan K.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Otto, Director of Legislative Affairs for the Animal Legal Defense Fund, is a comprehensive animal protection laws collection.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] It contains a detailed survey of the general animal protection and related statutes for all of the states, principal districts and territories of the United States of America, and for all of Canada; along with full-text versions of each jurisdiction's laws.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Animal law is being taught in a few European universities in Brazil, Argentina and Chile.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Animal law is being taught in a few European universities in Spain, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The Autonomous University of Barcelona (UAB), in Spain, is the only European university to offer a master's degree in Animal Law and Society (Derecho Animal y Sociedad).
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The highly interdisciplinary program, directed by Prof.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Teresa Giménez-Candela, is taught in Spanish and English.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] It aims to provide students knowledge of animals in the fields of law, ethology, nutrition and welfare, ethical dimensions, artistic representations and entertainment, organization and social responsibility.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The program is based on a comparative law perspective, keeping in mind the needs of society as a whole.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] A postgraduate diploma is also available in that specific field.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Initially, the Autonomous University of Barcelona Law School was the first Spanish university to officially offer optional courses in "Animal Law and Animal Welfare Law: comparative perspective (Derecho Animal y Derecho del Bienestar Animal: perspectiva comparada)" in 2007–2008.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Due to student demand, a Postgraduate Degree in Animal Law and Society was established in 2009–2010.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The first edition of the Master's program in Animal Law and Society was launched in 2011–2012 and is currently accepting students for its eighth edition (Oct.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] UAB also offers an online Master's in Animal Law and Society, and is currently accepting applications for its fifth edition (Jan.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] KIMEP University in Almaty, Kazakhstan, introduced a course of Animal Law in 2013 upon initiative of Dr.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Maria Baideldinova (Assistant Professor, KIMEP School of Law).
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] While still a burgeoning field in Africa, animal law is definitively growing.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] In 2022, the first Animal Law Course will be taught in South Africa by founding directors of Animal Law Reform South Africa, which will be an online course, giving access to the subject to South African and African students for the first time on the continent.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Regarding the campaign to change the status of animals as property, the animal rights activists have seen success in several countries.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] However, in 1999, the Swiss constitution was completely rewritten.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] A decade later, Germany guaranteed rights to animals in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The German Civil Code had been amended correspondingly in 1997.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The amendment, however, has not had much impact in German legal practice yet.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] In 2015 the National Assembly of the Province of Quebec adopted a modification of the Quebec Civil Code according animals the status of sentient beings instead of property, as previously.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The greatest success of the animal rights activists has certainly been the granting of basic rights to five great ape species in New Zealand in 1999.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] (The UK government banned experiments on great apes in 1986.) Some other countries have also banned or severely restricted the use of non-human great apes in research.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] The declaration wants to extend to the non-human apes the protection of three basic interests: the right to life, the protection of individual liberty, and the prohibition of torture.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-law] New Zealand has effectively phased out live exports for slaughter purposes since 2007 due to concerns about animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The **Animal Legal Defense Fund** is an American animal law advocacy organization.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Its stated mission is to protect the lives and advance the interests of animals through the legal system.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In addition to their national headquarters in Cotati, California, the Animal Legal Defense Fund maintains an office in Portland, Oregon.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund goes to court for animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] From filing high-impact lawsuits to providing *amicus curiae* briefs, its litigation work is a primary tool in the work to advance the interests of animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's team of expert staff attorneys may bring suit themselves, or it may retain outside counsel for representation.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Its civil actions on behalf of animals often include filing *amicus curiae* briefs arguing the case for recognition of the bonds between humans and nonhuman animals and filing formal complaints against government agencies charged with enforcing laws meant to protect animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's Criminal Justice Program is staffed by attorneys, including former prosecutors, with expertise in animal protection law who provide free legal assistance to prosecutors, law enforcement, and veterinarians handling animal cruelty cases.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] It also works with state legislators to strengthen criminal animal protection laws.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's Animal Law Program works closely with law students and law professionals to advance the emerging field of animal law.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Working to expand the practice and understanding of animal law in the legal community, the Animal Legal Defense Fund partners with attorneys and pro bono coordinators across the country.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The program utilizes these volunteers to support the Animal Legal Defense Fund's litigation, criminal justice, and legislative goals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund works at the state and local levels to advance important legislation.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Legislative Affairs Program advocates for laws that promote or protect the lives and interests of animals and opposes legislation that would be detrimental to animals’ well-being.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's annual report comprehensively surveys animal protection laws of all U.S. states and territories.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] It is the longest-running and most authoritative report of its kind, assessing the strength of each jurisdiction's animal protection laws by examining over 4,000 pages of statutes.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The report also highlights the top, middle and bottom tiers of jurisdictions and notes the "Best Five" and "Worst Five" states overall.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In December, the Supreme Court denied the foie gras industry's petition challenging California's ban on the sale of foie gras.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals' mandate went into immediate effect, banning foie gras in California.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund filed numerous amicus briefs in the six-plus years of litigation, urging courts to uphold the law.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In October, the Animal Legal Defense Fund and the National Council of Juvenile and Family Court Judges (NCJFCJ) announced a first-of-its-kind partnership to address judicial response in court cases related to animal cruelty.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In March 2018, a consumer protection lawsuit was filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund against Trader Joe's on behalf of an egg purchaser.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The lawsuit sought to stop Trader Joe's from deceptively and misleadingly labeling its cage-free eggs.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The consumer argued that Trader Joe's was violating multiple California consumer protection laws by selling cage-free eggs in cartons with representations of hens foraging in pastures, when the eggs were actually from industrial hen houses, where hens do not have access to the outdoors.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The case reached a settlement in June 2018, in which Trader Joe's agreed to pull the packaging not only in California but nationwide.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In the spring of 2018, after the Animal Legal Defense Fund announced its intent to sue Deer Haven Mini Zoo in Keymar, Maryland for violations of the federal Endangered Species Act and state cruelty laws, the owners agreed to voluntarily relinquish some of the animals on the property.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Two endangered lemurs, a bobcat, six arctic foxes, four cavies, and a coatimundi were removed from the unaccredited roadside menagerie and transferred to sanctuaries.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, a California judge ordered Manning Beef, a slaughterhouse, to pay $94,500 in attorneys' fees after Manning falsely accused Los Angeles Cow Save, a group that organized vigils for animals killed at the slaughterhouse, of trespassing.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The fees were awarded after the Animal Legal Defense Fund, the Law Offices of Matthew Strugar, and attorney Ryan Gordon filed an anti-SLAPP motion on behalf of the group.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] District Court of Utah ruled the Utah ag-gag statute was unconstitutional, the second decision against an ag-gag statute affirming it was unconstitutional.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Both rulings were due to lawsuits filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Ag-gag laws criminalize undercover investigations at factory farms and slaughterhouses that often expose serious animal cruelty and violations of environmental and safety laws.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the inhumane King Kong Zoological Park in North Carolina shut down permanently after the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed a lawsuit alleging the zoo's treatment of animals violated North Carolina's animal cruelty laws.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] North Carolina's unique civil animal cruelty law empowers concerned members of the public to report when criminal animal cruelty laws go ignored and under-enforced, as they did at the King Kong Zoo.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In September, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won a lawsuit against the Pennsylvania Deptartment of Agriculture for dogs suffering in puppy mills.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The department was forced to reinstate comprehensive regulations for commercial dog breeders.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The rules had prohibited some of the cruelest and most inhumane practices, such as keeping mother dogs in cages with metal wirestrand flooring and never letting mother dogs outside for exercise.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, the Animaland Zoological Park in Pennsylvania permanently shut down in response to a March 2016 lawsuit filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The lawsuit alleged that the zoo violated the Endangered Species Act and state wildlife laws by failing to provide adequate care for animals confined at the facility.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Two bears and an endangered wolf were relocated to sanctuaries that are capable of meeting their needs.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won an Endangered Species Act lawsuit on behalf of four tigers and three lemurs held in substandard captivity at Cricket Hollow Zoo, a roadside zoo in Iowa.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] This victory is the first time that animal advocates successfully used the Endangered Species Act to obtain a court order for the removal of captive animals from substandard conditions, and sets important precedent that isolation of social animals violates the Act.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In October, the California Coastal Commission voted at the Animal Legal Defense Fund's request that SeaWorld San Diego must discontinue its captive orca breeding program in order to proceed with its Blue World expansion plans at that facility.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the Animal Legal Defense Fund settled its public nuisance lawsuit against Jim Mack's Ice Cream to secure the release of a female black bear named Ricki from her 16-year confinement at the ice cream shop to the Colorado-based Wild Animal Sanctuary.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] District Court for the District of Idaho ruled that the state's ag-gag law, Idaho Code sec.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] 18-7042, violates the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the U.S.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Constitution, the first time a court had declared an ag-gag statute unconstitutional and a landmark victory for a broad-based public interest coalition of national nonprofits, including the Animal Legal Defense Fund, PETA, the ACLU of Idaho, and the Center for Food Safety.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund and PETA believe that the current confinement conditions are prohibited by the ESA.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] This may lead to Lolita being retired from performing and transferred to a seaside sanctuary.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In January 2014, Caltrans agreed to remove bird-killing nets at a local highway project, and vowed to use safer construction methods, after settling with the Animal Legal Defense Fund and conservation groups.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In July 2013, the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed the first lawsuit in the nation to challenge the constitutionality of an ag-gag law.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Utah's law, which criminalizes the videotaping on factory farms, attacks activity protected under the U.S.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Constitution's First and Fourteenth Amendments.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Also in July 2013, eleven bears were removed from gladiator-style bear pits at a North Carolina roadside zoo after the Animal Legal Defense Fund sent the Chief Saunooke Bear Park a letter threatening to sue for ongoing harm to the grizzlies.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In March, the Clay County (Kentucky) Circuit Court entered an agreed order of judgment resolving the Animal Legal Defense Fund's lawsuit against the county to stop systematic abuses at the local animal shelter.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Following the lawsuit, which was based on an undercover video, Cal-Cruz is no longer in operation, and the former owner may no longer work with animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, a North Carolina judge granted Ben the Bear permanent sanctuary at the Performing Animal Welfare Society as a result of a lawsuit against Jambbas Ranch—Animal Legal Defense Fund attorneys worked to represent the plaintiffs.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Ben had languished for years on cement in a chain-link kennel—he now has the chance to live like a bear should, with plenty of space to roam, play, and forage in his new habitat.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, Guam voted to dramatically strengthen the territory's laws protecting animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Guam's new legislation adopts robust minimum care standards and other definitions which mirror much of what is contained in the Animal Legal Defense Fund's model animal protection laws.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In November, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won its lawsuit to free Tony the Tiger from the Tiger Truck Stop in Grosse Tete, Louisiana.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The judge ordered the Louisiana Department of Wildlife and Fisheries to revoke the current permit and prohibited it from issuing any new permits to the Truck Stop.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Kenneth Lang Jr. pleaded guilty to animal cruelty in January 2010.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund secured permanent custody of seven horses rescued from Michael, Judy, and Gayle Keating, the abusive North Carolina owners who allowed them to starve nearly to death, in the case of ALDF v.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] On October 6, the United States Supreme Court directly addressed the issue of animal cruelty for the first time in more than fifteen years.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund submitted an amicus curiae brief in the case of U.S. v.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] Stevens, urging the Court to uphold the law and recognize that the prevention of cruelty to animals is a compelling government interest.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed lawsuits in Kentucky against Estill and Robertson Counties for neglecting their homeless animals, despite their legal requirement to provide basic humane care.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund called on Kentucky's legislature to push for comprehensive changes in its laws protecting horses and other animals.
[src:animal-law-review/animal-legal-defense-fund] In 2008, Kentucky ranked last in the nation for animal protection laws.
[src:animal-law-review/aubrey-watzek-library] The **Aubrey Watzek Library** is a library on the Lewis & Clark College campus, in Portland, Oregon.
[src:animal-law-review/aubrey-watzek-library] The building was designed by Paul Thiry and completed in 1967.
[src:animal-law-review/aubrey-watzek-library] The library doubled in size during renovations completed in the mid-1990s by Hoffman Construction.
[src:animal-law-review/aubrey-watzek-library] In 2016, a copy of the 1599 Geneva Bible was rediscovered in the library's basement.
[src:animal-law-review/aubrey-watzek-library] Since 2001, the library has housed the literature of the Lewis and Clark Expedition collection in a special collections facility.
[src:animal-law-review/aubrey-watzek-library] The William Stafford Archive was established in the special collections in 2008.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The Supreme Court uses its own unique citation style in its opinions, even though most of the justices and their law clerks obtained their legal education at law schools that use *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Furthermore, many state courts have their own citation rules that take precedence over the guide for documents filed with those courts.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Some of the local rules are simple modifications to *The Bluebook* system.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Delaware's Supreme Court has promulgated rules of citation for unreported cases markedly different from its standards, and custom in that state as to the citation format of the Delaware Uniform Citation code also differs from it.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] In other states, the local rules differ from *The Bluebook* in that they use their own style guides.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Attorneys in those states must be able to switch seamlessly between citation styles depending upon whether their work product is intended for a federal or state court.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] California has allowed citations in Bluebook as well as the state's own style manual, but many practitioners and courts continue recommending the *California Style Manual*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] An online-subscription version of *The Bluebook* was launched in 2008.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] A mobile version was launched in 2012 within the Rulebook app, which enables access for legal professionals to federal or state court rules, codes, and style manuals on iPads and other mobile devices.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] While legal citation manuals go as far back as *Modus Legendi Abbreviaturas in Utroque Iure*, published around 1475, there were very few examples prior to the 20th century; law professor Byron D.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Cooper mentions only a few short articles: "Rules for Citation" (*The American Law Review*, 1896) and "Methods of Citing Statute Law" (Ruppenthal, *Law Library Journal*, 1919).
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The *Uniform System of Citations* thus became a "pioneer" manual.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] According to Harvard, the origin of *The Bluebook* was a pamphlet for proper citation forms for articles in the *Harvard Law Review* written by its editor, Erwin Griswold.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] However, according to a 2016 study by two Yale librarians, Harvard's claim is incorrect.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] They trace the origin of *The Bluebook* to a 1920 publication by Karl Llewellyn at Yale on how to write law journal materials for the *Yale Law Journal*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Eventually, Harvard reversed course and joined the coalition by 1926.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Friendly, "Attorney General [Herbert] Brownell ... and I and two others [from Columbia and Pennsylvania] were the authors of the first edition of the *Bluebook*." Friendly has also sometimes been considered the creator of *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The cover of the 1926 *A Uniform System of Citation* was green.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The color was "brown from the second (1928) edition through the fifth (1936) edition.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] It was only with the sixth (1939) edition that it became blue." In 1939, the cover of the book was changed from brown to a "more patriotic blue", allegedly to avoid comparison with a color associated with Nazi Germany.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The eleventh edition, published in 1967, was actually white with a blue border.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The cover color returned to blue in the twelfth edition of 1976.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The full text of the first (1926) through the fifteenth (1991) editions is available on the official website.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] By 2011, *The Bluebook* was "the main guide and source of authority" on legal references for the past 90 years.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] It is recognized as the "gold standard" for legal references in the United States, even though it was originally designed only to help teach law students how to cite cases and other legal material.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Although other citation systems exist, they have limited acceptance, and in general, *The Bluebook* is followed in the legal citation as the most widely accepted citation style, called the "Bible", the "final arbiter", even the legal citation "Kama Sutra".
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Some states have adopted *The Bluebook* in full, while others have partially adopted *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] States such as Texas have supplements, such as *The Greenbook*, that merely address citation issues unique to Texas and otherwise follow *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The Solicitor General issues a style guide that is designed to supplement *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] This guide focuses on citation for practitioners, such as restraining law reviews to two typefaces: normal and italics.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Other changes are similarly minor, such as moving *supra* from before the page referenced to after the page number.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The guide does state that unless explicitly specified otherwise, *The Bluebook* rule takes precedence in the event of conflict.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] California used to require use of the *California Style Manual*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] In 2008, the California Supreme Court issued a rule giving an option of using either the *California Style Manual* or *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The two styles are significantly different in citing cases, in use of *ibid.* or *id.* (for **idem**), and in citing books and journals.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Michigan uses a separate official citation system issued as an administrative order of the Michigan Supreme Court.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] At over 500 pages for the 19th edition, *The Bluebook* is significantly more complicated than the citation systems used by most other fields.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Legal scholars have called for its replacement with a simpler system.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The University of Chicago uses the simplified "Maroonbook", and even simpler systems are in use by other parties.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] During his tenure on the United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit, Judge Richard Posner repeatedly criticized the *Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] In 1986, he wrote the article "Goodbye to the *Bluebook*," hoping that the Maroonbook would quickly overtake it.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] In 2011, he wrote the article "The *Bluebook* Blues," lamenting that the *Bluebook* remained dominant despite its increasing complexity, while providing the 885-word citation manual used among his law clerks.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Another dispute is over the copyright status of *The Bluebook*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Open-source advocates claim that *The Bluebook* is not protected under copyright because it is a critical piece of legal infrastructure.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Lawyers who represent the Bluebook publishing consortium claim that the "carefully curated examples, explanations and other textual materials" are protected by copyright.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Sprigman at NYU Law School prepared a "public-domain implementation of the *Bluebook*'s Uniform System of Citation," which his group calls *BabyBlue*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] In response to the HLRA letter to Sprigman, over 150 students, faculty, staff, and alumni of Harvard Law School signed a petition supporting *BabyBlue*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Yale and NYU students added their separate petitions supporting *BabyBlue*.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The posting also suggested that HLRA should "redirect the money it spends on legal fees ($185,664 in 2013)" to a more worthy purpose.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] For the first 50 years of the *Bluebook*'s history, the Harvard Law Review kept 100 percent of the revenues.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] In 1974, the editors of the *Columbia* and *University of Pennsylvania Law Reviews* and the *Yale Law Journal* apparently discovered this due to an indiscretion.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] They complained that Harvard was illegally keeping all profits from the first eleven editions, estimated to total $20,000 per year.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] After they threatened to sue, Harvard agreed to split the revenue: 40 percent for Harvard, 20 percent each for Columbia, Pennsylvania, and Yale; Harvard would continue to provide the production and distribution services.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] The law reviews have not disclosed the revenues of the *Bluebook* themselves, but revenues from the sale of the *Bluebook* have been estimated "in the millions of dollars".
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] A 2022 review of the *Harvard Law Review*'s non-profit disclosures found that the *Bluebook* had made $1.2 million in profits in 2020, with *The Harvard Law Review* taking an 8.5% cut of profits for administrative services and the remainder split equally among the four law reviews.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Profits from the *Bluebook* totaled $16 million between 2011 and 2020.
[src:animal-law-review/bluebook-infobox] Excluding the *University of Pennsylvania Law Review*, the law review's endowments total $59.4 million.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein serves as the Robert Walmsley University Professor at Harvard Law School.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He was previously a professor at the University of Chicago Law School from 1981 to 2008.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 2014, studies of legal publications found Sunstein to be the most frequently cited American legal scholar by a wide margin.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Cass Robert Sunstein was born on September 21, 1954, in Salem, Massachusetts, to Marian (née Goodrich), a teacher, and Cass Richard Sunstein, a builder.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He has said that as a teenager, he was briefly infatuated with the works of Ayn Rand, "[b]ut after about six weeks of enchantment, her books started to make me sick.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein graduated from Middlesex School in 1972.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He then went to Harvard University, where he was a member of the varsity squash team and an editor of the *Harvard Lampoon.* He graduated in 1975 with a Bachelor of Arts, *magna cum laude*.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He then attended Harvard Law School, where he was an executive editor of the *Harvard Civil Rights–Civil Liberties Law Review* and was on the winning team of the Ames Moot Court Competition.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He graduated in 1978 with a Juris Doctor, *magna cum laude*.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] After law school, Sunstein was a law clerk to Justice Benjamin Kaplan of the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court from 1978 to 1979 and to Justice Thurgood Marshall of the U.S.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] After his clerkships, Sunstein spent one year as an attorney-advisor in the U.S.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Department of Justice's Office of Legal Counsel.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 1981, he became an assistant professor of law at the University of Chicago Law School (1981–1983), where he also became an assistant professor in the Department of Political Science (1983–1985).
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 1985, Sunstein was made a full professor of both political science and law; in 1988, he was named the Karl N.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Llewellyn Professor of Jurisprudence in the Law School and Department of Political Science.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The university honored him in 1993 with its "distinguished service" accolade, permanently changing his title to Karl N.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Llewellyn Distinguished Service Professor of Jurisprudence in the Law School and Department of Political Science.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 2009, Sunstein was described by fellow Chicago professor Douglas G.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Baird as a "Chicago person through and through".
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein was the Samuel Rubin Visiting Professor of Law at Columbia Law School in the fall of 1986 and a visiting professor at Harvard Law School in the spring 1987, winter 2005, and spring 2007 terms.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He has taught courses in constitutional law, administrative law, and environmental law, as well as the required first-year course "Elements of the Law", which was an introduction to legal reasoning, legal theory, and the interdisciplinary study of law, including law and economics.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] On January 7, 2009, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Sunstein would be named to head the White House Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA).
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] That news generated controversy among progressive legal scholars and environmentalists.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein's confirmation was long blocked because of controversy over allegations about his political and academic views.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] On September 9, 2009, the Senate voted for cloture on Sunstein's nomination as Administrator of the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs, Office of Management and Budget.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The Senate confirmed Sunstein on September 10, 2009, in a 57–40 vote.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In his research on risk regulation, Sunstein is known for developing, together with Timur Kuran, the concept of availability cascades, wherein popular discussion of an idea is self-feeding and causes individuals to over weigh its importance.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] An Empirical Analysis of the Federal Judiciary* (2005), *Infotopia: How Many Minds Produce Knowledge* (2006), and, co-authored with Richard Thaler, *Nudge: Improving Decisions about Health, Wealth, and Happiness* (2008).
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein's 2006 book, *Infotopia: How Many Minds Produce Knowledge*, explores methods for aggregating information; it contains discussions of prediction markets, open-source software, and wikis.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein's 2004 book, *The Second Bill of Rights: FDR's Unfinished Revolution and Why We Need It More than Ever*, advocates the Second Bill of Rights proposed by Franklin D.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Among these rights are a right to an education, a right to a home, a right to health care, and a right to protection against monopolies; Sunstein argues that the Second Bill of Rights has had a large international impact and should be revived in the United States.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein co-authored *Nudge: Improving Decisions about Health, Wealth, and Happiness* (Yale University Press, 2008) with economist Richard Thaler of the University of Chicago.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] *Nudge* discusses how public and private organizations can help people make better choices in their daily lives.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The ideas in the book proved popular with politicians such as U.S.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] President Barack Obama, British Prime Minister David Cameron, and the British Conservative Party in general.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The "Nudge" idea has also been criticized.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Contributing to the anthology *Our American Story* (2019), Sunstein addressed the possibility of a shared American narrative.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein is a contributing editor to *The New Republic* and *The American Prospect* and is a frequent witness before congressional committees.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He played an active role in opposing the impeachment of Bill Clinton in 1998.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In recent years, Sunstein has been a guest writer on *The Volokh Conspiracy* blog as well as the blogs of law professors Lawrence Lessig (Harvard) and Jack Balkin (Yale).
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He is considered so prolific a writer that in 2007, an article in the legal publication *The Green Bag* coined the concept of a "Sunstein number" reflecting degrees of separation between various legal authors and Sunstein, paralleling the Erdős numbers sometimes assigned to mathematician authors.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He is a member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences (elected 1992), the American Law Institute (since 1990), and the American Philosophical Society (elected 2010).
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] He received an honorary doctorate from Copenhagen Business School.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In February 2020, he wrote an article for Bloomberg titled "The Cognitive Bias That Makes Us Panic About Coronavirus".
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In it he claimed that "A lot more people are more scared than they have any reason to be" and that "Most people in North America and Europe do not need to worry much about the risk of contracting the disease.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] That's true even for people who are traveling to nations such as Italy that have seen outbreaks of the disease." He attributed the excessive perceived risk to probability neglect.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] At the time of publication, there were 68 confirmed COVID-19 cases in the U.S., including one death, and approximately 1000 new daily cases worldwide, over 300 of which in Europe.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein joined the Department of Homeland Security in February 2021 as an advisor to the Biden administration on immigration policy.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Together with Daniel Kahneman and Olivier Sibony, Sunstein co-authored *Noise: A Flaw in Human Judgment*, which was published in May 2021.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Drawing not least upon legal examples, it treats unwanted variability in human judgments of the same problem, for instance, when court judges recommend vastly different sentences for the same crimes.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The book looks both at what 'noise in human judgment' is, how it can be detected, and how it can be reduced.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Since 2021, Sunstein has co-taught a class on the United States Supreme Court at Harvard alongside retired Justice Stephen Breyer.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein is a proponent of judicial minimalism, arguing that judges should focus primarily on deciding the case at hand, and avoid making sweeping changes to the law or decisions that have broad-reaching effects.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Some view him as liberal, despite Sunstein's public support for George W.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Roberts, as well as providing strongly maintained theoretical support for the death penalty.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Conservative libertarian legal scholar Richard A.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Epstein described Sunstein as "one of the more conservative players in the Obama administration".
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Much of his work also brings behavioral economics to bear on law, suggesting that the "rational actor" model will sometimes produce an inadequate understanding of how people will respond to legal intervention.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein has collaborated with academics who have training in behavioral economics, most notably Daniel Kahneman, Richard Thaler, and Christine M.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Jolls, to show how the theoretical assumptions of law and economics should be modified by new empirical findings about how people actually behave.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] According to Sunstein, the interpretation of federal law should be made not by judges but by the beliefs and commitments of the U.S. president and those around him.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] "There is no reason to believe that in the face of statutory ambiguity, the meaning of federal law should be settled by the inclinations and predispositions of federal judges.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The outcome should instead depend on the commitments and beliefs of the President and those who operate under him", argued Sunstein.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein (along with his coauthor Richard Thaler) has elaborated the theory of libertarian paternalism.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In arguing for this theory, he counsels thinkers/academics/politicians to embrace the findings of behavioral economics as applied to law, maintaining freedom of choice while also steering peoples' decisions in directions that will make their lives go better.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] With Thaler, he coined the term "choice architect".
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 2002, at the height of controversy over Bush's creation of military commissions without congressional approval, Sunstein stepped forward to insist, "Under existing law, President George W.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Bush has the legal authority to use military commissions" and that "President Bush's choice stands on firm legal ground." Sunstein scorned as "ludicrous" an argument from law professor George P.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Fletcher, who believed that the Supreme Court would find Bush's military commissions without any legal basis.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 2006, the Supreme Court found the tribunals illegal in *Hamdan v.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In his book *Democracy and the Problem of Free Speech* Sunstein says there is a need to reformulate First Amendment law.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Some of Sunstein's work has addressed the question of animal rights, as he co-authored a book dealing with the subject, has written papers on it, and was an invited speaker at "Facing Animals", an event at Harvard University described as "a groundbreaking panel on animals in ethics and the law".
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein's views on animal rights generated controversy when Sen.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.) blocked his appointment to the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs by Obama.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Chambliss objected to the introduction of *Animal Rights: Current Debates and New Directions*, a volume edited by Sunstein and his then-companion Martha Nussbaum.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] For example, under current law, if someone saw their neighbor beating a dog, they cannot sue for animal cruelty because they do not have legal standing to do so.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein suggests that granting standing to animals, actionable by other parties, could decrease animal cruelty by increasing the likelihood that animal abuse will be punished.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In *Nudge: Improving Decisions About Health, Wealth, and Happiness*, Sunstein proposes that government recognition of marriage be discontinued.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] "Under our proposal, the word marriage would no longer appear in any laws, and marriage licenses would no longer be offered or recognized by any level of government", argues Sunstein.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein addressed the Senate on July 11, 1996, advising against the Defense of Marriage Act.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein co-authored a 2008 paper with Adrian Vermeule, titled "Conspiracy Theories", dealing with the risks and possible government responses to conspiracy theories resulting from "cascades" of faulty information within groups that may ultimately lead to violence.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The authors declare that there are five hypothetical responses a government can take toward conspiracy theories: "We can readily imagine a series of possible responses.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] (1) Government might ban conspiracy theorizing.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] (2) Government might impose some kind of tax, financial or otherwise, on those who disseminate such theories.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] (3) Government might itself engage in counterspeech, marshaling arguments to discredit conspiracy theories.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] (4) Government might formally hire credible private parties to engage in counterspeech.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] (5) Government might engage in informal communication with such parties, encouraging them to help." However, the authors advocate that each "instrument has a distinctive set of potential effects, or costs and benefits, and each will have a place under imaginable conditions.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] There is a tradeoff between credibility and control, however.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The price of credibility is that government cannot be seen to control the independent experts." This position has been criticized by some commentators who argue that it would violate prohibitions on government propaganda aimed at domestic citizens.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein and Vermeule's proposed infiltrations have also been met by sharply critical scholarly responses.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In the 1980s and early 1990s, Sunstein was married to Lisa Ruddick, whom he met when both were undergraduates at Harvard.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] She was associate professor of English at the University of Chicago, specializing in British modernism, and is now retired.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Their daughter Ellyn is a journalist and photographer.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Thereafter, Sunstein dated Martha Nussbaum for almost a decade.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Nussbaum is a philosopher, classicist, and professor of law at the University of Chicago.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] On July 4, 2008, Sunstein married Samantha Power, a diplomat and government official who would serve as United States ambassador to the United Nations, whom he met when they both worked as campaign advisors to Barack Obama.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] The wedding took place in the Church of Mary Immaculate, in Lohar, Waterville, Ireland.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] They have two children: a son (born 2009) and a daughter (born 2012).
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] Sunstein is an avid amateur squash player who has played against professionals in PSA tournaments and in 2017 was ranked 449th in the world by the Professional Squash Association.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In July 2017, Sunstein was elected a Corresponding Fellow of the British Academy (FBA), the United Kingdom's national academy for the humanities and social sciences.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 2018 he was awarded the Holberg Prize for having "reshaped our understanding of the relationship between the modern regulatory state and constitutional law.
[src:animal-law-review/cass-r-sunstein] In 2026, he was made an Honorary Fellow of Trinity College Dublin.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] The "Ninth Circuit Review" surveys recent decisions from the Ninth Circuit involving federal environmental statutes, Native American rights, common law environmental protections, procedural aspects of citizen suits, and all other topics exploring environmental issues.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] "Clear the Air" provides a forum for critics and skeptics to respond to articles published in the journal.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] The quick publication schedule for these letters enables researchers and practitioners to solicit answers and information from subscribers.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] Professor Scott Crespi ranked *Environmental Law* as the third most influential environmental law review in the United States, behind Boalt’s *Ecology Law Quarterly* and the *Harvard Environmental Law Review*.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] The journal is printed on unbleached, 100% recycled post-consumer paper with soy ink.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] Established in 1969 by Dean Harold Wren and Professor Bill Williamson, *Environmental Law* was Lewis & Clark Law School’s first law review.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] The journal was launched amid the growing national awareness of environmental issues and was a catalyst behind the law school’s environmental and natural resources program, which is commonly ranked as the best in the nation.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] Throughout the mid-1960s and 1970s, the United States Congress enacted a series of significant environmental laws, including the Wilderness Act, National Environmental Policy Act, Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, and Endangered Species Act.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] During this time, President Richard Nixon acknowledged the establishment of the nation's first law review dedicated to environmental law by writing a letter to the journal to thank Lewis & Clark Law School for its participation in the national movement.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] *Environmental Law*, President Nixon stated, provided "fresh hope" for answering "the great question" of the Seventies.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] The letter was republished on the first page of the first volume of *Environmental Law* and followed by articles by Senator Edmund S.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] Muskie and Supreme Court Justice William O.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] Members are selected either by virtue of their grades during their first year of law school or by completing an anonymous writing competition, which is held during the summer months.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] The general membership of the journal determines the number of applicants that may be admitted.
[src:animal-law-review/environmental-law-law-review] Prospective students are required to have a minimum grade point average.
